statement:
Let \emph{T} be a linear transformation from 2D to 3D such that

\begin{align*}T\left(\left[\begin{array}{c}
1 \\ 1
\end{array}\right]\right) = \left[\begin{array}{c}
5Â \\ 2 \\ 1
\end{array}\right]\end{align*}

and

\begin{align*}T\left(\left[\begin{array}{c}
2 \\ 3
\end{array}\right]\right) = \left[\begin{array}{c} 1Â \\ 2 \\ 8
\end{array}\right]\end{align*}

What is

\begin{align*}T\left(\left[\begin{array}{c}
0 \\ 1
\end{array}\right]\right)?\end{align*}

sols:
Notice that I can write {[}0,1{]} in terms of the other two vectors
{[}2,3{]} and {[}1,1{]} via,

\begin{align*}\begin{bmatrix}
0\\
1
\end{bmatrix}
=
\begin{bmatrix}
2\\
3
\end{bmatrix}
-2
\begin{bmatrix}
1\\
1
\end{bmatrix}.\end{align*}

Now transformation are linear. This means that T(ax)=aT(x) and
T(x+y)=T(x)+T(y). Therefore,

\begin{align*}
T\left(\begin{bmatrix}0\\1\end{bmatrix}\right) &= T\left(\begin{bmatrix}2\\3\end{bmatrix}-2\begin{bmatrix}1\\1\end{bmatrix}\right) \\
&=T\left(\begin{bmatrix}2\\3\end{bmatrix}\right)-2T\left(\begin{bmatrix}1\\1\end{bmatrix}\right)\\
&=\begin{bmatrix}1\\2\\8\end{bmatrix}-2\begin{bmatrix}5\\2\\1\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}-9\\-2\\6\end{bmatrix}.\end{align*}

Therefore

\begin{align*}T\left(\begin{bmatrix}0\\1\end{bmatrix}\right)=\begin{bmatrix}-9\\-2\\6\end{bmatrix}.\end{align*}
